-- S-2 (soundness audit 2026-07-13): a duplicate top-level function — same
-- name, same arity, its OWN second type signature, no intervening decl — used
-- to be accepted with ZERO diagnostics by check/run/build alike: the second
-- definition silently shadowed the first as dead code (`greet` printed
-- "Hello, " forever; the "Bye, " clause was unreachable). The discriminator
-- fixed in compiler/frontend/resolve.mdk (DuplicateSignature): a legitimate
-- multi-clause function carries exactly ONE type signature for its name; two
-- signatures for the same top-level name is unambiguously two definitions.
-- .expected = REJECT — check/run/build must all now refuse this program with
-- "'greet' is already defined at line 1" (R-DUPLICATE-SIGNATURE), not
-- silently execute the first definition.
greet : String -> String
greet name = "Hello, " ++ name

greet : String -> String
greet name = "Bye, " ++ name

main : <IO> Unit
main = println (greet "World")
